<div class="teacher-notes">
    <h3>ğŸ“Š Assessment Rubric</h3>
    
    <p><strong>Question Formulation (4 points):</strong></p>
    <ul>
        <li><strong>4 - Excellent:</strong> Questions probe deeply, show understanding of different expertise areas, build on evidence</li>
        <li><strong>3 - Good:</strong> Questions are relevant and show some depth, connect to evidence</li>
        <li><strong>2 - Developing:</strong> Questions are basic but appropriate, some connection to evidence</li>
        <li><strong>1 - Beginning:</strong> Questions are superficial or disconnected from evidence</li>
    </ul>
    
    <p><strong>Evidence Analysis (4 points):</strong></p>
    <ul>
        <li><strong>4 - Excellent:</strong> Evaluates evidence quality, identifies patterns, acknowledges limitations</li>
        <li><strong>3 - Good:</strong> Shows understanding of evidence, makes some connections</li>
        <li><strong>2 - Developing:</strong> Basic understanding of evidence, few connections made</li>
        <li><strong>1 - Beginning:</strong> Little analysis of evidence quality or reliability</li>
    </ul>
</div>

<div class="teacher-notes">
    <h3>ğŸ  Extension Activities</h3>
    <ul>
        <li><strong>Research Project:</strong> Choose another NZ historical mystery to investigate using same questioning approach</li>
        <li><strong>Modern Connection:</strong> Apply Socratic questioning to current environmental issue (kauri dieback, kea conservation, etc.)</li>
        <li><strong>Cultural Learning:</strong> Interview whÄnau/community members about traditional decision-making processes</li>
        <li><strong>Digital Creation:</strong> Create infographic showing "How to Ask Expert Questions"</li>
    </ul>
</div>

